shot up to around 10% at the end of March from an official 3.5% rate in February that marked a 50-year low. Never before has the unemployment rate risen so much so quickly.\n\nThe states recording the biggest increases last week were California (878,727), Pennsylvania (405,880) and New York (366,403), based on unadjusted data.\n\nCalifornia, the nation's largest state, has accounted for about 10% of all new claims in the past two weeks.\n\nSee:\n\nThe level of claims might still be underestimated, though. Some states continue to have trouble handling the huge influx of applications. Their small staff and computers systems have been overwhelmed after years of exceeding low claims.\n\nBig picture: The stunningly large increase in new claims clearly shows just how much damage the pandemic has done to the U.S. economy. The federal government is rushing to distribute more than $2 trillion in relief to businesses and households and provide a lifeline for the economy.\n\nRead:\n\nIt might not be enough, but it will help the economy in the short run. Millions of Americans who have lost their jobs or been furloughed might even get more money from unemployment benefits than they would have gotten in wages under their old jobs.\n\nRead:\n\nWhat they are saying? \"From extremely bad to even worse,\" said senior economist Andrew Grantham of CIBC World Markets, adding that the unemployment rate is likely to exceed 10% in the near future.\n\nMarket reaction: The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.03% and S&P 500 SPX, +0.33% were set to open higher in Thursday trades. Stocks have been badly battered over the past month. The 10-year Treasury yield TMUBMUSD10Y, 0.616% edged up to 0.59%.", "source": {"uri": "marketwatch.com", "dataType": "news", "title": "MarketWatch"}, "authors": [{"uri": "jeffry_bartash@marketwatch.com", "name": "Jeffry Bartash", "type": "author", "isAgency": false}], "concepts": [{"uri": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recession", "type": "wiki", "score": 4, "labe